• A correlogram or correlation matrix allows to analyse the relationship between each pair of numeric variables in a dataset.

  • It gives a quick overview of the whole dataset. It is more used for exploratory purpose than explanatory.

Scatterplot matrix with ggpairs()

library(GGally)
ggpairs(iris[1:4])

Change plot types

library(GGally)
 
data(tips, package = "reshape")
head(tips)
##   total_bill  tip    sex smoker day   time size
## 1      16.99 1.01 Female     No Sun Dinner    2
## 2      10.34 1.66   Male     No Sun Dinner    3
## 3      21.01 3.50   Male     No Sun Dinner    3
## 4      23.68 3.31   Male     No Sun Dinner    2
## 5      24.59 3.61 Female     No Sun Dinner    4
## 6      25.29 4.71   Male     No Sun Dinner    4

ggpairs(
  tips[, c(1, 3, 4, 2)],
  upper = list(continuous = "density", combo = "box_no_facet"),
  lower = list(continuous = "points", combo = "dot_no_facet")
)

Visualize correlation with ggcorr()

nba <- read.csv("../data/ppg2008.csv")
head(nba)
##             Name  G  MIN  PTS  FGM  FGA   FGP FTM FTA   FTP X3PM X3PA  X3PP ORB DRB TRB AST STL BLK  TO  PF
## 1   Dwyane Wade  79 38.6 30.2 10.8 22.0 0.491 7.5 9.8 0.765  1.1  3.5 0.317 1.1 3.9 5.0 7.5 2.2 1.3 3.4 2.3
## 2  LeBron James  81 37.7 28.4  9.7 19.9 0.489 7.3 9.4 0.780  1.6  4.7 0.344 1.3 6.3 7.6 7.2 1.7 1.1 3.0 1.7
## 3   Kobe Bryant  82 36.2 26.8  9.8 20.9 0.467 5.9 6.9 0.856  1.4  4.1 0.351 1.1 4.1 5.2 4.9 1.5 0.5 2.6 2.3
## 4 Dirk Nowitzki  81 37.7 25.9  9.6 20.0 0.479 6.0 6.7 0.890  0.8  2.1 0.359 1.1 7.3 8.4 2.4 0.8 0.8 1.9 2.2
## 5 Danny Granger  67 36.2 25.8  8.5 19.1 0.447 6.0 6.9 0.878  2.7  6.7 0.404 0.7 4.4 5.1 2.7 1.0 1.4 2.5 3.1
## 6  Kevin Durant  74 39.0 25.3  8.9 18.8 0.476 6.1 7.1 0.863  1.3  3.1 0.422 1.0 5.5 6.5 2.8 1.3 0.7 3.0 1.8

# uses a continuous color scale
ggcorr(nba[, 2:15])

# switch to categorical colors
ggcorr(nba[, 2:15], nbreaks = 5)

# controlling the color palette
ggcorr(nba[, 2:15], low = "steelblue", mid = "white", high = "darkred")

# use a ColorBrewer palette
ggcorr(nba[, 2:15], nbreaks = 4, palette = "RdGy")

# controlling the coefficient labels
ggcorr(nba[, 2:15], label = TRUE, label_size = 3, label_round = 2, label_alpha = TRUE)

ggcorr(nba[, 2:15],name = expression(rho),geom = "circle",max_size = 10,min_size = 2,size = 3,
       hjust = 0.75,nbreaks = 6,angle = -45,palette = "PuOr" # colorblind safe, photocopy-able
)

# styling the correlation coefficients
ggcorr(nba[, 2:15], geom = "text", nbreaks = 5, palette = "RdYlBu", hjust = 1, 
       label = TRUE, label_alpha = 0.5)

# highlights all correlation coefficients superior to 0.5 or inferior to −0.5
ggcorr(nba[, 2:15], geom = "blank", label = TRUE, hjust = 0.75) +
  geom_point(size = 10, aes(color = coefficient > 0, alpha = abs(coefficient) > 0.5)) +
  scale_alpha_manual(values = c("TRUE" = 0.25, "FALSE" = 0)) + guides(color = FALSE, alpha = FALSE)

Python Seaborn pairplot in R

import seaborn as sns
df = sns.load_dataset('iris')
sns_plot = sns.pairplot(df)

# with regression
sns_plot = sns.pairplot(df, kind="reg")

sns_plot = sns.pairplot(df, kind="scatter", 
  hue="species", markers=["o", "s", "D"], 
  palette="Set2")
